    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>April 28— 1878</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I sincerely wish that I could give you any information about your specimens; but I have never studied the genus Geum or attended to monstrosities or sudden deviations of structure.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                    <p>I may, however, remark that the supression of one sex is not a rare abnormality.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Wishing you success in your observations, I remain | Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
           
            
            
        </div> 
         
         
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><hi rend="italic">Geum</hi> is a genus of about fifty species in the rose family; it is closely related to <hi rend="italic">Potentilla</hi>. Whitelegge had evidently sent specimens of <hi rend="italic">Geum</hi>, but no letter from him discussing these has been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Whitelegge continued to investigate forms of <hi rend="italic">Geum rivale</hi> that had only male and hermaphrodite flowers on the same stem (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11522.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Thomas Whitelegge, 21 May 1878</ref>). <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3069.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hermann Müller</ref> later mentioned Whitelegge’s discovery that <hi rend="italic">Geum rivale</hi> was occasionally andromonoecious (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5700.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">H. Müller 1883</ref>, p. 229).</note>	
        </div>   
       
